A simple idea is to put everything in `Map`s, including the type name used for the original API, and how to create the strongly-typed items.

You&#39;d have two maps:

    private static final Map&lt;Class&lt;?&gt;, String&gt; typeNames = Map.of(
            Vegetable.class, &quot;vegetables&quot;,
            Berry.class, &quot;berries&quot;,
            Shape.class, &quot;shapes&quot;
    );

    private static final Map&lt;Class&lt;?&gt;, Function&lt;String, ?&gt;&gt; constructors = Map.of(
            // assuming constructors that take the item&#39;s name exist
            Vegetable.class, Vegetable::new,
            Berry.class, Berry::new,
            Shape.class, Shape::new
    );

You can also combine the type name and the `Function&lt;String, ?&gt;` into a class - then you&#39;d only need one map:

```
@AllArgsConstructor
@Getter
class ItemInfo {
    private final String typeName;
    private final Function&lt;String, ?&gt; factory;
}

private static final Map&lt;Class&lt;?&gt;, ItemInfo&gt; knownItemTypes = ...
```

And then use the `Class&lt;T&gt;` parameter that `getStronglyTyped` takes to access the maps:

    @SuppressWarnings(&quot;unchecked&quot;)
    public static &lt;T&gt; List&lt;T&gt; getStronglyTyped(Class&lt;T&gt; type, ItemFinder finder) {
        var typeName = typeNames.get(type);
        if (typeName == null) {
            throw new RuntimeException(&quot;Unknown type!&quot;);
        }
        return (List&lt;T&gt;)finder.getItemsByType(typeName).stream().map(
                x -&gt; constructors.get(type).apply(x.getName())
        ).toList();
    }

You can also create a (sealed) interface that `Vegetable`, `Fruit` and `Shape` implement, and constrain `T` to that, for extra safety.

Item class 

       abstract class Item {
            private final String name;
            public Item(String name) {
                this.name = name;
            }
            public String getName() {
                return name;
            }
            @Override
            public String toString() {
                return getClass().getSimpleName() + &quot;{name:&#180;&quot; + name + &quot;&#180;}&quot;;
            }
        }

Berry class

    public class Berry extends Item {
        public Berry(String name) {
            super(name);
        }
    }

Shape class

    public class Shape extends Item {
        public Shape(String name) {
            super(name);
        }
    }

Vegetable class

    public class Vegetable extends Item{
        public Vegetable(String name) {
            super(name);
        }
    }

Main

    public class Main {
        private static final List&lt;Item&gt; items = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(Arrays.asList(
                new Vegetable(&quot;Lettuce&quot;),
                new Vegetable(&quot;Tomato&quot;),
                new Berry(&quot;Strawberry&quot;),
                new Berry(&quot;Cranberry&quot;),
                new Shape(&quot;Square&quot;),
                new Shape(&quot;Triangle&quot;)
        ));
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            List&lt;Shape&gt; shapes = getItemsByType(Shape.class);
            System.out.println(shapes);
            List&lt;Berry&gt; berries = getItemsByType(Berry.class);
            System.out.println(berries);
            List&lt;Vegetable&gt; vegetables = getItemsByType(Vegetable.class);
            System.out.println(vegetables);
        }
    
    
        public static &lt;T extends Item&gt; List&lt;T&gt; getItemsByType(Class&lt;T&gt; tClass) {
            return items.stream()
                    .filter(item -&gt; item.getClass().getSimpleName().equals(tClass.getSimpleName()))
                    .map(tClass::cast)
                    .collect(Collectors.toList());
        }
    }

